## Purpose
Mapping is the primary feature of Forkumentos. It will become the largest and most complex module.
This rule captures engineering decisions for the mapping domain so future agents do not reinvent or contradict decisions already made.
It begins sparse and grows alongside the module.

## Scope
Any file inside `lib/features/mapping/` and any test that exercises mapping behavior.

## Core Principles
- The conceptual model of a mapping operation is: **source column → transformation → target field**. Every abstraction in this module maps to one of these three concepts or to their relationships.
- A mapping operation is stateless in its definition but stateful in its execution. The definition (what maps to what) is a model; the execution result is a separate state.
- Conflicts in mapping (e.g., two source columns mapping to the same target field) are surfaced as warnings visible to the user — they are never silently resolved by the system.
- Mapping preview is computed from the mapping definition — it is always a derived state, never stored independently.
- The mapping domain does not own persistence. It provides its model; `features/project/` owns the save lifecycle.

## DO
- Represent a mapping definition as an immutable model (Freezed) in `features/mapping/domain/`.
- Distinguish clearly between `MappingDefinition` (what the user configured) and `MappingResult` (the outcome of applying it).
- Surface conflicts as a typed collection on the result: `List<MappingConflict>`, never as thrown exceptions.

## DON'T
- Compute mapping results inside a widget's `build()` method.
- Persist mapping state directly from the mapping notifier — delegate to the project save mechanism.
- Mix transformation logic with column selection logic in the same notifier.

## NEVER
- Silently drop a source column that cannot be mapped. Always surface it as an unresolved mapping.
- Allow the mapping state to become inconsistent with the active project state.

## GOOD Example
A user maps two source columns to the same target field.
Correct response: `MappingResult.conflicts` contains a `DuplicateTargetConflict`. The UI shows a warning indicator. The mapping remains usable.

## BAD Example
A user maps two source columns to the same target field.
Wrong response: The second mapping silently overwrites the first. No conflict is reported.

## Decision Rules
Is a new concept part of the mapping definition (what the user configures)? → `domain/` as an immutable model.
Is it the result of executing a mapping? → `domain/` as a separate result model.
Is it a UI-specific concern (selected row, scroll position)? → Presentation layer provider, never the domain model.

## Conflict Resolution
`architecture_boundaries.mdc` governs import rules. `state_management.mdc` governs provider structure. This rule adds mapping-specific constraints on top of both — it takes precedence for decisions within this module.
